  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Level:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957 (Monetary Transactions)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- These often mirror federal provisions but can have unique state-specific requirements\n\nThese laws generally:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Impose reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Provide mechanisms for asset forfeiture\n\nInternational organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) also provide guidelines and standards for combating money laundering globally.\n\nThe primary goals of these statutes are to:\n- Detect and prevent criminal financial activities\n- Trace and disrupt illegal money flows\n- Prosecute individuals and organizations involved in money laundering",
